`crates/ctx-cage` is a self-contained crate that builds and runs an offline,
bind-mounted `bwrap` sandbox around an agent process, brokers the sandbox's
only network egress through a host-side proxy, and drives a single run's
prepare→run→teardown lifecycle behind one `execute()` entry point. External
callers get `lifecycle::execute`, the bwrap-arg builder, and proxy
request-rewrite logic; nothing else in the workspace should construct bwrap
flags or touch the API key directly.

The three subtrees are tightly interlocked around ADR-046/ADR-049: `assets/`
supplies the two files (`cage-nsswitch.conf`, `cage-resolv.conf`) that make the
sandboxed resolver fail slow instead of busy-looping, embedded into the binary
via `lib.rs`'s `include_str!` and bind-mounted by `src/`'s lifecycle/env code;
`tests/` is the only place that verifies both halves of that contract actually
hold (`bwrap_build.rs` checks the mount happens, `cage_assets.rs` checks the
asset's content isn't loopback-only). Changing the resolv.conf asset, the
`CAGE_RESOLV_PATH` bind constant, or the mount call in `lifecycle/env.rs`
requires updating all three subtrees together, since only their combination
proves the invariant.

Secrets never cross into the sandbox — `runtime.rs` and `lifecycle/env.rs`
independently enforce this, and only `proxy.rs` (host side) ever touches the
real API key, reached via a UNIX socket bind-mounted at `/run/ctx/api.sock`.
`cage-rules.md` (assets) is embedded and mounted at `/opt/cage/rules.md`
(src), the one path constant that both an asset file and crate code must
agree on by name.

No `intent.md` exists anywhere in this subtree, so there is no intent to
diverge from.